You are building the frontend settings page and extending the API client for an AI email outreach platform. The frontend is Next.js 16 at `/Users/tanishqsingh/Desktop/yash desktop files/projects/outreach-proj/frontend-v2/`.

## What you must build

### 1. Extend `src/lib/api.ts`
Add these new functions to the EXISTING file (append, don't rewrite):

```typescript
// Types for settings
export interface UserSettings {
  provider: "openrouter" | "openai" | "anthropic" | "gemini";
  model: string;
  has_openrouter_key: boolean;
  openrouter_key_hint?: string;
  has_openai_key: boolean;
  has_anthropic_key: boolean;
  has_gemini_key: boolean;
}

export interface ModelInfo {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  context_length: number;
  provider: string;
  free: boolean;
}

export interface ModelsResponse {
  models: ModelInfo[];
}

// Functions to add:
export async function getSettings(): Promise<UserSettings>
export async function saveSettings(data: {
  provider?: string;
  model?: string;
  openrouter_key?: string;
  openai_key?: string;
  anthropic_key?: string;
  gemini_key?: string;
}): Promise<{ success: boolean }>
export async function listModels(): Promise<ModelsResponse>
export async function devLogin(email: string): Promise<{ access_token: string; refresh_token: string; token_type: string; user: { id: string; email: string } }>
```

All use the existing `apiFetch` helper. `devLogin` posts to `/api/v1/auth/dev-login`.

### 2. Create `src/app/settings/page.tsx`
A full settings page with:
- **API Keys section**: Input fields for OpenRouter, OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini keys. Each field shows `••••••••` placeholder with a "key hint" suffix if already saved (e.g. `...e008`). Has an eye-toggle to show/hide. "Save" button per section OR one global save.
- **Model selection section**: Fetches `listModels()` and shows a grid/list of model cards. User selects one. Free models get a "Free" badge. Currently selected model is highlighted.
- **Provider selection**: Shows which provider the selected model belongs to (auto-detected from model ID or explicit selection).

Use the existing design system CSS variables (var(--bg), var(--fg), var(--accent), etc.), the `Icon` component at `@/components/ui/Icon`, `Sidebar`, `Topbar` layout components. Match the dark theme aesthetic of other pages (see dashboard/page.tsx for reference style).

The page must:
1. On mount: call `getSettings()` to load current config, call `listModels()` to load model list
2. On save: call `saveSettings()` with changed values, show success toast (just a temporary state banner)
3. Show loading states

File path: `src/app/settings/page.tsx`

### 3. Update `src/components/layout/Sidebar.tsx`
Make sidebar items navigable using Next.js `Link` and `usePathname`. Current sidebar items must link to:
- "New campaign" → `/campaign/new`
- "Campaigns" section items → `/dashboard`  
- "Settings" → `/settings`

The sidebar currently has hardcoded items. Update to use `useRouter` / `Link` for navigation and highlight the active item based on `usePathname()`.

### 4. Update `src/app/auth/page.tsx`
The page currently calls `googleAuthUrl()` for all login buttons. Add a **dev mode bypass** section that shows only when `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV === 'development'` OR always visible (simpler):

Add below the existing buttons a dev section:
```tsx
{/* Dev mode quick login */}
<div style={{ marginTop: 16, padding: 12, border: "0.5px dashed var(--border-strong)", borderRadius: 8 }}>
  <div style={{ fontSize: 11, color: "var(--fg-3)", marginBottom: 8 }}>Dev login</div>
  <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: 8 }}>
    <input 
      className="field" 
      placeholder="dev@example.com" 
      value={devEmail} 
      onChange={e => setDevEmail(e.target.value)}
      style={{ flex: 1, height: 32, fontSize: 12 }}
    />
    <button className="btn btn-sm" onClick={handleDevLogin}>Login</button>
  </div>
</div>
```

`handleDevLogin` calls `devLogin(devEmail)`, saves token to localStorage, redirects to `/dashboard`.

### 5. Add `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV=development` to `.env.local`

## Design reference
Look at `src/app/dashboard/page.tsx` for the CSS classes and inline style patterns to follow. Key classes: `shell`, `main`, `sidebar`, `btn`, `btn-primary`, `btn-sm`, `field`, `badge`, `b-sent`, `b-draft`. Use `var(--bg-1)`, `var(--border)`, `var(--fg-2)` etc.

## Files to read first
Read these before writing:
- `src/app/dashboard/page.tsx` (for style reference)
- `src/lib/api.ts` (to append to it correctly)
- `src/components/layout/Sidebar.tsx` (to update it)
- `src/app/auth/page.tsx` (to update it)
- `src/types/index.ts` (to know existing types)
- `.env.local` (to update it)

## Rules
- Do NOT rewrite `api.ts` — append the new functions and types
- The settings page must compile — no TypeScript errors
- Keep the exact visual style of the app (dark theme, monospace accents)
- After writing everything, run: `cd /Users/tanishqsingh/Desktop/yash\ desktop\ files/projects/outreach-proj/frontend-v2 && bun run build 2>&1 | tail -20`

Return summary of every file created/modified and whether build passes.

